ASDA - Geostatistics Lecture 1: Demo

General

Install packages

If you have not done so already, install the required packages using

geostat_pkgs <- c("sf", "sp", "geoR",  "gstat", "automap", "intamap", "tidyverse", "pacman", "tmap", "tmaptools", "spData",
                  "elevatr", "stars")
install.packages(geostat_pkgs )
remotes::install_github("wmgeolab/rgeoboundaries")

(Only do this once)

Get Help

ls("package:sp") help(package = sp)

Analysis Example - The meuse data

Description

This data set gives locations and top soil heavy metal concentrations (ppm), along with a number of soil and landscape variables, collected in a flood plain of the river Meuse, near the village Stein. The data comes with the sp package in R.

Plotting geometry

Format

This data frame contains the following columns:

  • a numeric vector; x-coordinate (m) in RDM (Dutch topographical map coordinates)
  • [y] a numeric vector; y-coordinate (m) in RDM (Dutch topographical map coordinates)
  • [cadmium] topsoil cadmium concentration, ppm.; note that zero cadmium values in the original data set have been shifted to 0.2 (half the lowest non-zero value)
  • [copper] topsoil copper concentration, ppm.
  • [lead] topsoil lead concentration, ppm.
  • [zinc] topsoil zinc concentration, ppm.
  • [elev] relative elevation
  • [dist] distance to river Meuse; obtained from the nearest cell in , which in turn was derived by a spread (spatial distance) GIS operation, therefore it is accurate up to 20 metres; normalized \([0,1]\)
  • [om] organic matter, as percentage
  • [ffreq] flooding frequency class
  • [soil] soil type
  • [lime] lime class
  • [landuse] landuse class
  • [dist.m] distance to river Meuse (metres), as obtained during the field survey

References

  • P.A. Burrough, R.A. McDonnell, 1998. Principles of Geographical Information Systems. Oxford University Press.
  • (http:/www.gstat.org/)

# Plot Points
meuse_ptsa <- tm_shape(meuse.area) + tm_polygons() +
  tm_shape(meuse) +
  tm_dots(col = "black", 
          title="Sampled locations", size=0.2) 

meuse_ptsb <- tm_shape(meuse.area) + tm_polygons() +
  tm_shape(meuse) +
  tm_dots(col="zinc", palette = "RdBu", auto.palette.mapping = FALSE,
          title="Zinc Values", size=0.2) +
  tm_legend(legend.position=c("left","top"))

meuse_pts_bub <- tm_shape(meuse.area) + tm_polygons() +
  tm_shape(meuse) +
  tm_bubbles(size=c("zinc"),
             col=c("orange"),
             border.col="black",
             border.alpha = .75,
             scale=.7) +
  tm_legend(legend.position=c("left","top"))

# Plot Values
meuse_pts_vals <- tm_shape(meuse.area) + tm_polygons() +
  tm_shape(meuse) +
  tm_text("zinc", size = 0.3)

# Combine Plots
tmap_arrange(meuse_ptsa , meuse_ptsb , meuse_pts_bub , meuse_pts_vals)

meuseg1 <- SpatialPixelsDataFrame(coords, meuse.grid)

Plotting Extras

Interactive maps

tmap_mode("view")
tmap mode set to interactive viewing
qtm(meuse)
tmap_mode("plot")
tmap mode set to plotting

Plotting lines

cc <- coordinates(meuse) 
m.sl <- SpatialLines(list(Lines(list(Line(cc)), "line1"))) 
proj4string(m.sl) <- CRS("+init=epsg:28992")
plot(m.sl) # plots lines connecting all the points

Combining multiple elements

tmap_mode("view")
tmap mode set to interactive viewing
qtm(meuse) + qtm(m.sl) + qtm(meuse.riv.sp, fill="lightblue")

Mapping a continous variable

Plot a continuous variable, using a particular class interval style.

See: ArcGIS Data Classification Methods

m_zequal = tm_shape(meuse.area) + tm_polygons() +
  tm_shape(meuse) +
  tm_dots(col="zinc", style = "equal",  size=0.2, legend.hist = TRUE) +
  tm_layout(title = 'style = "equal"') + 
  tm_legend(legend.position=c("right","bottom"), outside = TRUE, hist.width = 2)

m_zpretty = tm_shape(meuse.area) + tm_polygons() +
  tm_shape(meuse) +
  tm_dots(col="zinc", style = "pretty",  size=0.2, legend.hist = TRUE) +
  tm_layout(title = 'style = "pretty"')  + 
  tm_legend(legend.position=c("right","bottom"), outside = TRUE, hist.width = 2)

m_zquantile = tm_shape(meuse.area) + tm_polygons() +
  tm_shape(meuse) +
  tm_dots(col="zinc", style = "quantile",  size=0.2, legend.hist = TRUE) +           
  tm_layout(title = 'style = "quantile"')  + 
  tm_legend(legend.position=c("right","bottom"), outside = TRUE, hist.width = 2)

m_zjenks = tm_shape(meuse.area) + tm_polygons() +
  tm_shape(meuse) +
  tm_dots(col="zinc", style = "jenks",  size=0.2, legend.hist = TRUE) +
  tm_layout(title = 'style = "jenks"')  + 
  tm_legend(legend.position=c("right","bottom"), outside = TRUE, hist.width = 2)
         
tmap_arrange(m_zpretty, m_zequal, m_zquantile, m_zjenks)

Creating a Spatial Object

library(sf)
library(ggplot2)

# set the seed for the random number generator
set.seed(4)

# Create a sixteen square polygon
bb <- st_make_grid(st_bbox(c(xmin = 0, xmax = 10, ymin = 0, ymax = 10)), n = 10)
grd <- st_as_sf(bb)
grd$ID <- 1:length(bb)



# Generate simple random sample
test <- st_sample(grd, size = 100, type = "random")

ggplot() + 
  geom_sf(data = grd) + 
  geom_sf(data = test) + 
  ggtitle("Simple")

# Generate systematic random sample
test <- st_sample(grd, size = 100, type = "regular")

ggplot() + 
  geom_sf(data = grd) + 
  geom_sf(data = test) + 
  ggtitle("Systematic")

# Generate stratified random sample
grd2 <- st_cast(grd, "MULTIPOLYGON")
st_crs(grd2) <- 5070

test <- st_sample(grd2, size = 100, type = "random", by_polygon = TRUE)

ggplot() + 
  geom_sf(data = grd) + 
  geom_sf(data = test) + 
  ggtitle("Stratified")
